In Swing you have to attach any elements you wish to display to a JFrame (often via intermediary JPanels, etc.), which you must then set as visible. As pointed out in comments, you never add the east_pane to the JFrame in your code.

There are two ways you might go about this: 

The quick and easy option would be to add the line 

    window.add(east_pane, BorderLayout.EAST); 

on the line after the declaration of east_pane. 

A better option, however, would be to make your buildEast() and buildNorth() methods return JPanel objects and then integrate them into the JFrame inside the GUI1 method like so (note that we can now also scope the window object more narrowly):

    public GUI1()
    {
        //Set name and dimensions of window
        JFrame window = new JFrame(&quot;Program 2&quot;);
        window.setBounds(187, 218, 700, 450);
    
        window.add(buildEast(), BorderLayout.EAST);
        window.add(buildNorth(), BorderLayout.NORTH);
    
        window.setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE);
        window.setVisible(true); //default is invisible window
    }
    public JPanel buildEast()
    {
        //Create and add panel to east of window
        JPanel east_pane = new JPanel();
        //Add a title for the slider
        JLabel slideLabel = new JLabel (&quot;Change Year&quot;);
        east_pane.add(slideLabel);
    
    
        final int YEAR_MIN = 1990;
        final int YEAR_MAX = 2019;
        int selectYear = 2000;
        JSlider yearSlide = new JSlider(JSlider.VERTICAL, YEAR_MIN, YEAR_MAX, selectYear);
    
        //Setup for slide labels
        yearSlide.setMajorTickSpacing(4);
        yearSlide.setMinorTickSpacing(2);
        yearSlide.setPaintTicks(true);
        yearSlide.setPaintLabels(true);
    
        east_pane.add(yearSlide);
        return east_pane;
    }

Going this route will make your UI much easier to deal with as it grows in size.

The reason Swing works this way (and by extension, the reason you didn&#39;t get any errors but were able to use those print statements) is that Swing allows you to dynamically swap out UI elements on the fly. While this may be beyond the scope of your assignment, consider a tabbed application. It may not be (and likely isn&#39;t) desirable to destroy a tab each time it becomes hidden, just to have to re-create it moments later (as this takes time, it may contain data or processing logic, etc.). And, obviously, you wouldn&#39;t want it to be visible all the time. The answer then is to simply not display that tab until you want to do so.

